On 2098/12/15, the second Foundation Centennial Summit will be held. The event was created as a means by the Overseer Council to assess the state of the Foundation, what it had achieved over the previous century, and its future.

[[div class="darkbox"]]
= //NEO-SITE-19. CONFERENCE ROOM.//

//[Five individuals sit beside a large slab of black rock located at the center of the room. O5-13 is situated at the table’s head. Windows line the walls, offering a view of the moon and the ground below. Several Foundation exclusionary cities can be seen in the distance. O5-5 enters the room.]//

**O5-5:** I was about to apologize for my lateness, but it appears I’m not the latest by a fair margin.

**O5-13:** Rebekah, I must be the bearer of bad news. The rest won’t be coming.

//[Rebekah walks to the table and takes a seat. 7 remain empty.]//

**O5-5:** The other council members told you this?

**O5-13:** The other council members do not exist.

**O5-5:** Sophia, I’m not quite sure I follow-

**O5-6:** Well, I see the plan to fill her in before the Summit went //swimmingly.//

//[O5-13 waves her hand at O5-6.]//

**O5-13:** Ms. Dark, your comment is neither helpful nor appreciated.

//[A mechanical voice is emitted from O5-10. His lips do not move.]//

**O5-10:** Agreed. 

**O5-13:** Perhaps I should elaborate. When the Black Moon Incident occurred, the only survivors on the Council were the previous O5-5, O5-8, O5-11, and I. No-one’s seen nor heard from O5-11 in 20 years; he’s still alive, but holed up in his personal fortress. O5-5 has passed. Which leaves myself and -8.

//[The Council glances towards O5-8. The old woman sits huddled in her seat, staring down at the table. She mumbles indiscernible words to herself. O5-6 leans across the table, and whispers to O5-5.]//

**O5-6:** In case you were wondering, it’s easier to just mark Eight as an abstention on any votes we hold. Her mind left some time ago.

**O5-13:** -1 died at Yellowstone, trying to prepare 2000 for activation. -2 slit her own throat whilst I was on the other end of the phone. O5-9 turned to Fifthism in a miserable attempt to transcend… but we all know how that ended. The others died. I don’t know how, but I know they died. Like everything did.

**O5-8:** Never trust a pentagram. Too many corners.

**O5-13:** In the aftermath, we did what we could. As the creator of ORACLE, it was natural to offer Thomas a seat at the table in O5-4’s position.

**O5-4:** ORACLE’s creation was very much a team effort, Sophia.

**O5-13:** Indeed, a team //you// led. And then, when we merged with Vincent and Lenora’s respective organizations, we offered them the positions of O5-10 and O5-6 respectively. And that was our team, for a time. Until the passing of your predecessor – and now you’re here.

**O5-5:** Why only bring me on board? Why not replace the other roles? 

//[O5-13 turns to O5-4. The latter nods. O5-13 pulls out an electronic device and begins to type.]//

**O5-4:** ORACLE. You were the first person it recommended for the Council. Your predecessor was a military man, I think you bring the same qualities he did. Bold. Straight talking.

**O5-5:** I’ve been part of the Council for months. Worked with you all. And you didn’t think to mention this to me? 

**O5-6:** We’re mentioning it to you now. “Months” is nothing for an Overseer. 

//[O5-13 stops typing.]//

**O5-13:** ORACLE?

//[Silence.]//

**O5-13:** ORACLE, I have a question.

//[Silence.]//

**O5-13:** I've disabled 7070-Ω. Shall we commence the meeting?

**O5-5:** ORACLE isn't to be included in the Summit discussions?

//[O5-4 glances at O5-13, before turning to O5-5.]//

**O5-4:** No. The... the Summit stipulations state only Council members can partake. Whilst important, ORACLE is technically not a Council member.

**O5-5:** Will the Administrator at least be in attendance? 

//[The question is met by silence.]//

**O5-5:** I asked if-

**O5-13:** No. No, the Administrator will not be in attendance.

**O5-5:** Why is that the case?

**O5-13:** The Administrator looked out at the world following the Black Moon Incident, and he saw the destruction. The devastation. The damaged state of his beloved Foundation, with over half his handpicked Council dead. And he decided he could look upon that world no longer. 

**O5-6:** Things got tough; he threw in the towel.

**O5-13:** You know it was not that simple.

**O5-5:** But I… I’ve spoken to him. When I was promoted to the Council, he called me directly to ask. There are annual video messages from him sent to the whole Foundation!

**O5-4:** What you saw, who you spoke to… it was ORACLE. After the Howling, we didn’t think what was left of us could survive knowing what happened to the Administrator. He was – //is// – the figurehead. We couldn’t tell the survivors the Administrator was gone.

**O5-6:** You should tell her everything.

**O5-4:** I will. I //am//.

**O5-5:** What else-

//[O5-5 is interrupted by a coughing sound. O5-8 retches, and a small ball of mucus is ejected onto the table.]//

**O5-8:** Family business to attend to.

//[An O5 hierophant, until now unseen in the shadows of the room, runs forward and wipes O5-8’s mouth, before retreating away from the table.]//

**O5-5:** What else is it that I need to know? 

**O5-4:** ORACLE’s power, its sheer capacity, is obtained, in part through the thaumaturgic inscriptions – //[he taps his head]// on our brains. There was a… progenitor for this though. When…when the Administrator…

**O5-6:** Would you like me to say it for you? 

**O5-4:** No no, thank you Six. The Administrator had a wealth of knowledge, of the Foundation, of the anomalous. And an abundance of anomalous knowledge can change you – The way your brain is wired. And that stays with you even after death. We didn’t want to let that power go to waste. In the aftermath of the Howling, we couldn’t afford to. 

**O5-5:** What did you do, exactly?

**O5-4:** We installed the Administrator – what was left of him – into ORACLE. And it worked. It worked beautifully. ORACLE changed, upgraded, instantaneously. It gave us a fighting chance. 

**O5-5:** The details expunged from the logs…

**O5-4:** In the cold light of day, we did what needed to be done. Without the Administrator, ORACLE would not have worked. Without ORACLE, the Foundation would have collapsed. And without the Foundation, there was no hope for the remnants of humanity. Even the Global Reconstruction Effort understood that much.  At the time, we were desperate.

**O5-13:** Maybe once. But no more. It's time to shut it down. 

//[05-5 turns and stares at 13.]//

**O5-5:** Shut down ORACLE?

**O5-13:** The Centennial Summit is held to determine the future of the Foundation. To decide if the organization is still necessary. To ask whether or not this course is sustainable. So no, Rebekah, not just ORACLE. ORACLE and the Foundation.

**O5-5:** Thirteen, the Foundation is the only reason why humanity still exists right now.

**O5-13:** You call this humanity?

**O5-5:** The Foundation pulled me from a survivor’s tribe when I was 10, I know what the absence of humanity is. 

**O5-13:** Rebekah, blind loyalty is dispensed of at our rank for good reason. Look at those cities, filled to the brim with human cattle. It's an attempt to cling to what we once had. 

**O5-5:** Living in an exclusionary city is better than living in the Blightlands! In the wild, having to fight for yourself, not knowing what’ll come next! They’re happy in those cities!

**O5-13:** They can’t be anything else.

**O5-5:** The Foundation succeeded. To anyone in those cities, the Veil had never fallen. The Howling had never occurred. We did the impossible and //contained// the Black Moon!

**O5-13:** Then why does the sky still bleed? We didn’t contain anything, Rebekah. It’s more like we wrapped a bandage made of amnestics and synapse-switchers over it. ORACLE’s directive was to uphold the Foundation. But, at some point, what was best for us was not best for the world.

**O5-8:** Bandages never truly stem the bleeding. That requires devotion.

//[O5-5 turns to the rest of the council.]//

**O5-5:** Won’t any of you say something? This is madness.

**O5-4:** We categorically -- //categorically// -- have not contained the Black Moon. If anything, I fear worse is still to come. We've never proven the cause of the Black Moon Incident, but I have my theories. We know the Black Blight wasn't in the Moon naturally -- the Foundation conducted plenty of tectonic studies prior to 2048, and there was nothing to indicate its existence. 

**O5-5:** How does this relate to ORACLE?

**O5-4:** Let me finish. We also know, that the Black Moon was connected to the database corruption. Vincent and I have been researching this and we don't think the Black Moon caused the database corruption. We believe it was the other way around. The Foundation caused the Moon to bleed.

**O5-5:** That's not possible.

**O5-10:** In 2048, SCiPNET was the greatest repository of information on the anomalous ever created. To bring together that knowledge into one place, to combine all that power in ones and zeroes, and to leave it there together. The database corruption, the Black Moon. It is all connected.

**O5-4:** I developed my suspicions decades ago, after installing the Administrator. It's like I said: an abundance of anomalous knowledge can change you. And we're making the same mistake again, except this time housing that information inside the world's most powerful AI. I created ORACLE. The machine is my life’s work. It was designed to help us survive the worst catastrophe mankind had ever experienced. But we use it now to tell us how to //live//. We’ve become dependent on it.    

**O5-10:** I always admired the Foundation, even prior to joining you. An adamant pursuit of knowledge and scientific research. But under ORACLE, that aspect of our work has been quashed. Look at the design of our cities. We yearn for the past instead of facing the future.

//[O5-6 stands from her chair, and gestures towards the landscape seen through the window.]//

**O5-6:** Do we really think that //this// is the best possible future for humanity? Stagnated livestock in a global containment chamber. We haven’t detected new anomalies since before the Howling. The old ones are dead, or rotting away in the Blightlands. 

**O5-5:** But what happens without ORACLE? What happens when people begin to starve to death, and when the inhibitors shut down? When the cities open up, and they realize their lives are a lie? Without the Foundation, how will they get resources? I've spent my career rescuing survivors from the Blightlands, I don't want to damn them again!

**O5-13:** Humanity’s greatest strength is our adaptability. Our ability to make our own path. They will find a way. The hydroponic farms in each city are now active, ORACLE isn’t needed to keep them running. It's time to give people back what we took from them.

**O5-5:** We should at least ask ORACLE what it-

**O5-4:** No. Enough is enough. This is our decision to make. 

**O5-5:** You’re suicidal. You’re damning everyone if you do this. It’s genocide. Why are none of you–

**O5-13:** Rebekah.

//[O5-13 calmly stands from her chair, walks over to O5-5. She takes her hand.]//

**O5-13:** When the Foundation found you, scared and alone on the banks of the Mississippi River in the shadow of SCP-3000, you were not there because of ORACLE. It was luck, luck and your own ingenuity. No scripted event, no problem statement and response. You survived. As a member of the Foundation, you’ve made your own choices. Excelled in what you do, done your best to protect others. It’s time we gave everyone the chance to do the same. 

**O5-5:** Sophia… this is the only world I’ve ever known. Even without the Foundation, we still have an obligation to help those people. If we're going to pull the rug out from underneath them and say that we were wrong to put it there in the first place, imagine how that will make them feel? If you're admitting fault, you're admitting that we stole their lives. I... I put so many people in those cities, knowing I was doing the right thing. How am I supposed to suddenly feel remorse? I know we were doing the right thing! 

**O5-13:** I know. But I promise you – another world is possible. This will not be an end. But a beginning. You’ll have free reign to help who you want, regardless of mission briefing arriving in your inbox.

//[O5-13 lets go of O5-5’s hand, and returns to her seat.]//

**O5-13:** Initiate vote. 

//[Electronic screens from the table, one in front of each Council member.]//

//[The screens flicker to life, each displays a single sentence:]//

[[div class="lightbox"]]
= [[size 150%]] {{SHUT DOWN ORACLE. DISSOLVE THE FOUNDATION.}}[[/size]]
[[/div]]

//[Below the directive, three options, “YEA”, “ABSTAIN”, “NAY”, are illuminated by a slight glow.]//

//[O5-4, O5-6, O5-10, and O5-13 all vote. O5-5’s finger hovers in front of the screen.]//

**O5-13:** This is your call, Rebekah. The vote needs to be unanimous. I’ve said all I-

**O5-8:** End it.

//[The O5s turn to O5-8.]//

**O5-8:** This whole charade has run for far too long.

**O5-13:** Maria… is that you? 

**O5-8:** So focused on the how. We forgot about the why.

//[O5-13 stands, and makes her way around the table to O5-8.]//

**O5-13:** Maria?

//[O5-8 forcefully presses the screen in front of her. Her finger lands on the affirmative vote. She stares at O5-5.]//

**O5-8:** The decisions hardest to make are often the most frightening.

//[O5-8’s gaze drifts, falling to her lap. She resumes mumbling.]//

//[O5-5 votes.]//

